1.From epidemic to pandemic

In December 2019, COVID-19 coronavirus was first identified in the Wuhan region of China. By March 11, 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) categorized the COVID-19 outbreak as a pandemic. A lot has happened in the months in between with major outbreaks in Iran, South Korea, and Italy.

We know that COVID-19 spreads through respiratory droplets, such as through coughing, sneezing, or speaking. But, how quickly did the virus spread across the globe? And, can we see any effect from country-wide policies, like shutdowns and quarantines?

Fortunately, organizations around the world have been collecting data so that governments can monitor and learn from this pandemic. Notably, the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering created a publicly available data repository to consolidate this data from sources like the WHO, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), and the Ministry of Health from multiple countries.

In this notebook, you will visualize COVID-19 data from the first several weeks of the outbreak to see at what point this virus became a global pandemic.

Please note that information and data regarding COVID-19 is frequently being updated. The data used in this project was pulled on March 17, 2020, and should not be considered to be the most up to date data available.

3. Confirmed cases throughout the world

The table above shows the cumulative confirmed cases of COVID-19 worldwide by date. Just reading numbers in a table makes it hard to get a sense of the scale and growth of the outbreak. Let’s draw a line plot to visualize the confirmed cases worldwide.

Filter the table, only choose the data row whose type is confirmed case

cfm <- coronavirus %>%
  filter(type == 'confirmed')

Add columns that show total case by date and cumlative number of cases accross date

total_cfm <- cfm %>%
group_by(date) %>%
summarise(total_cases = sum(cases)) %>%
mutate(cum_cases = cumsum(total_cases))

Draw a line plot of cumulative cases vs. date

ggplot(total_cfm, aes(y=cum_cases, x=date)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylab('Cumulative confirmed cases')

5.Vietnam Coronavirus Status

Fetching Vietnam Data Corona Virus from ‘coronavirus’ library

Filter the data

vietnam_corona <- coronavirus %>%
  select(-c("province","lat","long")) %>%
  filter(country == "Vietnam")

vietnam_corona <- vietnam_corona %>%
      group_by(date, type) %>%
      summarise(tt_case=sum(cases))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'date'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
vietnam_corona <- vietnam_corona %>%
     group_by(type) %>%
     mutate(cum_cases = cumsum(tt_case))
vn_cases <- vietnam_corona %>%
  group_by(date) %>% 
  filter(type == 'confirmed')
vn_cases

ggplot(vn_cases, aes(x=date, y=cum_cases)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', se=FALSE) +
  ylab("Cumulative confirmed cases")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Plot show confirmed, death and recovered cases in Vietnam

vietnam_type <- ggplot(vietnam_corona) + geom_line(aes(x=date,y=cum_cases,group=type,color=type))
vietnam_type

Add some important milestones give us a clearer understanding how Vietnamese virus trend has shifted during these period The milestone was refenrenced from wikipedia: COVID-19 pandemic in Vietnam (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic_in_Vietnam)

#create a tibble for Vietnamese corona virus event
vietnam_events <- tribble(
  ~ date, ~ event,
  "2020-01-23", "First infected case in Vietnam",
  "2020-07-25", "Da Nang Outbreak",
  "2021-01-28", "Hai Duong outbreak",
  "2021-04-27", "Ho Chi Minh outbreak") %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(date))
vietnam_events
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##   date       event                         
##   <date>     <chr>                         
## 1 2020-01-23 First infected case in Vietnam
## 2 2020-07-25 Da Nang Outbreak              
## 3 2021-01-28 Hai Duong outbreak            
## 4 2021-04-27 Ho Chi Minh outbreak
# Using who_events, add vertical dashed lines with an xintercept at date
# and text at date, labeled by event, and at 100000 on the y-axis
vietnam_type +
  geom_vline(data=vietnam_events, aes(xintercept=date), linetype="dashed") +
  geom_text(data=vietnam_events,aes(x=date, label=event), y=6000, size=1.7)

6.Vietnam compare to Asean Countries

*Retrieved the data from “coronavirus” library, filter Asean countries, comprises of: -Brunei -Malaysia -East Timor -Indonesia -Philipines -Singapore -Cambodia -Laos -Myanmar -Malaysia -Thailand -Vietnam

aseancountries <-c("Brunei","Cambodia","Malaysia","Timor-Leste","Malaysia","Philippines","Singapore","Laos","Burma","Thailand","Vietnam","Indonesia")
asean <- coronavirus %>%
  filter(country %in% aseancountries) 
str(asean)
## 'data.frame':    16236 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ date    : Date, format: "2020-01-22" "2020-01-22" ...
##  $ province: chr  "" "" "" "" ...
##  $ country : chr  "Brunei" "Burma" "Cambodia" "Indonesia" ...
##  $ lat     : num  4.535 21.916 11.55 -0.789 19.856 ...
##  $ long    : num  115 96 105 114 102 ...
##  $ type    : chr  "confirmed" "confirmed" "confirmed" "confirmed" ...
##  $ cases   : num  0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 4 0 ...
asean %>%
  filter(type=="confirmed") %>%
group_by(country) %>%
summarise(confirmed_cases_by_asean = sum(cases)) %>%
ggplot(aes(x = country, y = confirmed_cases_by_asean)) +
geom_col(position = "dodge") +
geom_text(aes(label=confirmed_cases_by_asean), position=position_dodge(width=0.9), vjust=-0.25,size=3)

#world total death cases by date
death_asean <- asean %>%
  filter(type == 'death') %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
summarise(d_asean_cases = sum(cases))
#world total confirmed cases by date
confirmed_asean <- asean %>%
  filter(type == 'confirmed') %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
summarise(c_asean_cases = sum(cases))
#world total confirmed cases by date
recovered_asean <- asean %>%
  filter(type == 'recovered') %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
summarise(r_asean_cases = sum(cases))
case_type_asean =  confirmed_asean %>%
  full_join(recovered_asean,by="country") %>%
  full_join(death_asean,by="country")
case_type_asean
